add increasing bitscore when see a case where start and end seem on different strands

had 11 cases where start and end seem on different strands without adding this bump up in those cases. four out of four tested were fixed with this fix. None of four had omega. (Actually I ended up hand checking and none of 11 had the omega intron. However, I worry this approach may be slightly flawed though in that I didn't propogate over that increase in bitscore cutoff where checked against full genomic with the intron, and thus a shift to less hits with the full genomic could be influenced AND MISSED by this and I just got lucky that none of those involved had omega intron? By the way it isn't easy to proppgate since the checking for omega intron is actually a separate script so I can't just re-adjust setting of bitscore cutoff in one place but would need to pass it.)

Close #1 - make work with chromosome subsets again and bonus outcome was fixing order along X-axis

Making it work again with chromosomes or subsets of chromosomes alone, seems to have also addressed issues with order. Seems applying categorical to chromosomes but not the other columns in the data allowed ordering to match the GTF as a result. That was totally serendipitous because I had with all columns that were strings as `category` and it put human chromosome X immediately after seven (and eleven in front of ten) and the yeast roman numerals were jumbled. It got horrible as far as order of chromosomes when I made all `object`, which most strings should be, but when I made `seqname` category and all other string columns as `object` then the human and the yeast were both ordered matching the GTF. Which is what I had wanted all along. Fixing to work with chromosome subsets required adding `observed=True` to the groupby steps so that not all categoricals used, resulting in just those with rows. So I addressed the original and resulting later-indicated issues in https://github.com/fomightez/sequencework/issues/1 .

Close #1 - make work with chromosome subsets again and bonus outcome was fixing order along X-axis

Making it work again with chromosomes or subsets of chromosomes alone, seems to have also addressed issues with order. Seems applying categorical to chromosomes but not the other columns in the data allowed ordering to match the GTF as a result. That was totally serendipitous because I had with all columns that were strings as `category` and it put human chromosome X immediately after seven (and eleven in front of ten) and the yeast roman numerals were jumbled. It got horrible as far as order of chromosomes when I made all `object`, which most strings should be, but when I made `seqname` categoery and all other string columns as `object` then the human and the yeast were both ordered matching the GTF. Which is what I had wanted all along. Fixing to work with chromosome subsets required adding `observed=True` to the groupby steps so that not all categoricals used, resulting in just those with rows. So I addressed the original and resulting later-indicated issues in https://github.com/fomightez/sequencework/issues/1 .

change to `is None` which is better 

change to `is None`, which is better according to  PEP 8 Style Guide, the preferred way to compare something to None are the patterns if cond is None or if cond is not None.

The statement is is used for object identity, it checks if objects refer to the same instance. Since None is a singleton this statement can be used to safely check whether a variable points to None.

The == and != statement refers to equality, which means they call the __eq__ method of the referred objects. But this function can differ depending on the implementation of the objects.
